    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our offensive engine is centered around **James Wood** (76.28) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.98), both of whom capitalize on high-upside matchups against high-xERA arms. **James Wood** is our premier play, leading off against Fuentes; his ability to translate a +19% SP skill boost into high-scoring efficiency makes him the cornerstone of our production. Similarly, **Mickey Moniak** benefits from a massive +19% boost against the aging Walker Buehler, compounded by a rare +14% park factor and the specific statistical advantage of facing a pitcher with a slow delivery, which creates an ideal environment for **Mickey Moniak** to exploit the base paths\u2014a critical consideration given our strategic emphasis on SB volume.\n\nIn the middle of the order, **Vinnie Pasquantino** (68.43) offers excellent stability, anchored by a +14% platoon edge and a favorable wind forecast providing a +5% boost against Bassitt. While **Josh Naylor** (66.61) and **Austin Riley** (66.19) remain solid anchors in the heart of our lineup, the most intriguing bench decision was the omission of **Corbin Carroll** (53.11). Despite his elite profile, **Corbin Carroll** was relegated to the bench because he draws a difficult assignment against Anthony Kay (2.60 xERA). The optimizer favored the higher efficiency scores of **Jose Caballero** (61.91) and **Seiya Suzuki** (62.00) due to their platoon advantages and superior situational matchups. Note that we are monitoring potential lineup fluidity; while we have accounted for **Luis Campusano** and **Dalton Rushing** in the bottom third, their scores remain conservative until official cards are posted. We are avoiding exposure to high-K environments against Fried and Suarez, which suppresses the outlook for **Trevor Story**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, and **Giancarlo Stanton**, though they remain high-floor options compared to the remaining depth on our bench.",
